description: From Middle English importen, from Old French emporter, importer, from Latin importō (“bring in from abroad, import”, verb), from in (“in, at, on; into”) + portō (“I carry, bear; convey”).

entries.meaning: (countable) Something brought in from an exterior source, especially for sale or trade.

examples: It was a matter of great import.

entries.meaning: (countable, Philippines) A foreigner playing in a sports league.

verbs.description: import (third-person singular simple present imports, present participle importing, simple past and past participle imported)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To bring (something) in from a foreign country, especially for sale or trade.
(transitive) To load a file into a software application from another version or system.
examples: How can I import files from older versions of this application?

description: From Italian importare, and French importer, from Latin importō.

verbs.description: import (third-person singular simple present imports, present participle importing, simple past and past participle imported)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To be important; to be significant; to be of consequence.
examples: See how much it importeth to learn to take Time by the Fore-Top.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To be of importance to (someone or something).
examples: If I endure it, what imports it you?

entries.meaning: (transitive) To be incumbent on (someone to do something).
examples: It imports us to get all the aid and assistance we can.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To be important or crucial to (that something happen).
examples: It much imports your house That all should be made clear.
Every petition  […]  doth  […]  always import a multitude of speakers together.
